title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Sleep and Stress Level I









Hours of sleep is number of overnight hours from waking up that morning (i.e., no lag).
To allow for a chi-square test of association (next slide) …

The few days with less than 6 (n=2) or more than 9 (n=6) hours of sleep were combined with 6 and 9 hours to form “≤6 h” and “≥9 h” categories.
The few days with “Tough, but things done” (n=8), “Tough, but getting through” (n=7), and “Tears, hanging on” (n=4) levels were combined into one level called “Tough.”

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Sleep and Stress Level II



While there is some evidence for fewer “tough” days with increasing amount of sleep, ultimately NO significant association between hours of sleep and stress level was detected (p=0.131).
[Not shown] There was no association between stress level and hours of sleep one day (p=0.707) and two days (p=0.057) previous.
[Not shown] There was a weak association between stress level and hours of sleep seven days previous (p=0.031). There were somewhat fewer “tough” stress days than expected with less hours of sleep seven days previous.

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Workouts and Eating Habits I









To allow for a chi-square test of association (next slide) …

The “Competition” days were dropped (n=3) (can be added back later when more competitions are added).
The two “Not good, ..” levels (n=6 and 0) were combined to one “Not good” level.

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Workouts and Eating Habits II



There is a significant association between training type and eating habits (p=0.005).
It appears that you eat more balanced meals and fewer “not good” meals on your training days, as compared to your rest days.

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Sleep and Body Feels I









Hours of sleep is number of overnight hours from waking up that morning (i.e., no lag).
To allow for a chi-square test of association (next slide) …

The few days with less than 6 (n=2) or more than 9 (n=6) hours of sleep were combined with 6 and 9 hours to form “≤6 h” and “≥9 h” categories.
The “Sick/Injured/Can’t” level was dropped (n=0).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Sleep and Body Feels II



There is NO significant association between how your body felt and hours of sleep that day (p=0.225) and two days previous (p=0.963) previous [Not shown].
[Not shown] There was an association between how your body felt and hours of sleep one day previous (p=0.023), with slightly fewer than expected “Sore, need trainer” and “Fine, getting it done” days with more sleep (>8 hr) one day previous.
[Not shown] There was an association between how your body felt and hours of sleep seven days previous (p=0.038). There were somewhat more than expected “Sore, need trainer” and “Fine, getting it done” days with more sleep and more than expected “Amazing, could PR” days with less sleep seven days previous.

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Eating Habits and How Body Feels I
text:
Eating Habits and How Body Feels I









To allow for a chi-square test of association, unused levels of “body feels” and “eating habits” were dropped as on previous slides
There was NO significant association between eating habits for the day and how your body felt that day (p=0.664).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Eating Habits and How Body Feels II
text:
Eating Habits and How Body Feels II









There was NO significant association between eating habits from previous day and how your body felt – one day previous (p=0.561, shown), two days previous (p=0.693, not shown), and seven days previous (p=0.459, not shown).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Eating Habits and Sleep I









To allow for a chi-square test of association, unused levels of “eating habits” were dropped and sleep amounts were combined as on previous slides
There was a significant association between eating habits for the day and how much you slept that night (p=0.029). There was a tendency to sleep less when you ate worse (and sleep more when you ate better).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Eating Habits and How Body Feels II
text:
Eating Habits and How Body Feels II









There was NO significant association between eating habits from previous days and how much you slept that day – one day previous (p=0.078, shown), two days previous (p=0.105, not shown), and two days previous (p=0.516, not shown).
There was slight evidence (but not significant) that you slept more on the day following when you did not eat well (shown).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Eating Habits and Sleep II









There was NO significant association between eating habits from previous days and how much you slept that day – one day previous (p=0.078, shown), two days previous (p=0.105, not shown), and seven days previous (p=0.516, not shown).
There was slight evidence (but not significant) that you slept more on the day following when you did not eat well (shown).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Electrolytes and How Body Feels I
text:
Electrolytes and How Body Feels I









To allow for a chi-square test of association, unused levels of “body feels” were dropped and electrolyte levels were pooled into “yes” (had electrolytes) or “no”
There was NO significant association between having electrolytes for the day and how your body felt that day (p=0.469).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Electrolytes and How Body Feels II
text:
Electrolytes and How Body Feels II









There was NO significant association between having electrolytes on previous days and how your body felt – one day previous (p=0.427, shown), two days previous (p=0.060, not shown), and seven days previous (p=0.355, not shown).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Alcohol and How Body Feels I
text:
Alcohol and How Body Feels I









To allow for a chi-square test of association, unused levels of “body feels” were dropped and alcohol levels were pooled into “yes” (had electrolytes) or “no”
There was NO significant association between consuming alcohol for the day and how your body felt that day (p=0.304).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
section: Alcohol and How Body Feels II
text:
Alcohol and How Body Feels II









There was NO significant association between consuming alcohol on previous days and how your body felt – one day previous (p=0.593, shown), two days previous (p=0.666, not shown), and seven days previous (p=0.629, not shown).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Alcohol and Stress I









To allow for a chi-square test of association, a singular “tough” stress level was created (as preciously) and alcohol levels were pooled into “yes” (had electrolytes) or “no”
There was NO significant association between consuming alcohol for the day and stress levels that day (p=0.245).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Alcohol and Stress II









There was NO significant association between consuming alcohol on previous days and stress level – one day previous (p=0.052, shown), two days previous (p=0.071, not shown), and seven days previous (p=0.727, not shown).
However, there is weak evidence for more “Happy, under control” days when having consumed alcohol the previous day (shown)

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Period and Sleep









To allow for a chi-square test of association sleep amounts were combined as on previous slides
There was NO a significant association between being on your period and how much you slept that night (p=0.747).

title: Journey’s Daily Data 2023-24
text:
Period and Stress









To allow for a chi-square test of association, a singular “tough” stress level was created (as preciously)
There was NO significant association between being on your period and stress level that day (p=0.445).
